  "statement": {
    "en": "DUB regulators of YAP/TAZ activity in mesothelioma and head and neck cancer",
    "ja": null,
    "latex": null,
    "preview_source": "tier7-ingest-v0.2",
    "summary": "The Hippo pathway is evolutionarily conserved to regulate multiple biological processes including development, organ size, apoptosis, and tissue regeneration, thereby maintaining tissue homeostasis. This tumour-suppressive signalling cascade acts inactivates the downstream effectors and oncogenes YAP/TAZ, preventing their binding to the TEAD transcription factors. Disruption of the Hippo pathway and aberrant YAP/TAZ activity are observed in many cancers such as pleural mesothelioma (PM) and head and neck squamous cell carcinoma (HNSCC), where there are known genetic drivers. Deubiquitinating enzymes (DUBs) have been identified as direct or indirect regulators of the pathway. However, questions remain unresolved, notably around the specificity of their interaction with the Hippo components "
  },
